Q6. To create the scatterplot we add a layer with geom_point.
murders %>% ggplot(aes(x = , y = )) + geom_point()
except we have to define the two variables x and y. Fill this out with the correct variable names.

murders %>% ggplot(aes(x = population, y = total)) +
  geom_point()

Q7. Note that if we don’t use argument names, we can obtain the same plot by making sure we enter the variable names in the right order like this:
murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total)) + geom_point() Remake the plot but now with total in the x-axis and population in the y-axis.

murders %>% ggplot(aes(total, population)) + 
  geom_point()

Q8. If instead of points we want to add text, we can use the geom_text() or geom_label() geometries. The following code
murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total)) + geom_label()
will give us the error message. Why is this?

# Correct case of using geom_label()
murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total, label = abb)) + geom_label()

Answer : In ggplot(), there is an argument label which applied to other methods globally. If there isn’t label in ggplot(), we need to let geom_label know what character to use in the plot. So the answer is (b).

Q9. Change the color of the labels to blue. How will we do this?

# Correct case of using colour argument
murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total, label = abb)) + geom_label(colour = 'blue')

Answer : Because we want all colors to be blue, we do not need to map colors, just use the color argument in geom_label.

Q10. Now suppose we want to use color to represent the different regions. In this case which of the following is most appropriate:

# Correct case of using colour argument
murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total, label = abb, color = region)) + geom_label(size = 3)

Answer : Adding a column called color is not good case, because it can cause storage waste of dataset. So the correct case is using the color argument in ggplot.

Q11. Now we are going to change the x-axis to a log scale to account for the fact the distribution of population is skewed. Let’s start by defining an object p holding the plot we have made up to now
p <- murders %>% ggplot(aes(population, total, label = abb, color = region)) + geom_label()
To change the y-axis to a log scale we learned about the scale_x_log10() function. Add this layer to the object p to change the scale and render the plot.

p <- murders %>%
  ggplot(aes(population, total, label = abb, color = region)) + geom_label(size = 3) 

p + 
  scale_x_log10()

08 Visualizing data distributions : Exercise 16 page - 24 page

Q1. In the murders dataset, the region is a categorical variable and the following is its distribution: To the closest 5%, what proportion of the states are in the North Central region?

murders %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(proportion = round(n/sum(n)*100, 2))
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##   region            n proportion
##   <fct>         <int>      <dbl>
## 1 Northeast         9       17.6
## 2 South            17       33.3
## 3 North Central    12       23.5
## 4 West             13       25.5

Answer : The proportion of the states in the North Central region is about 23.5 %.

Q2. Which of the following is true:

Answer :
(a) The graph above is a histogram -> Barplot(proprtion)
(b) The graph above shows only four numbers with a bar plot.
(c) Categories are not numbers, so it does not make sense to graph the distribution. -> We make graph using value ‘proportion’.
(d) The colors, not the height of the bars, describe the distribution -> It distributes categories of region.

male_height <- heights %>% 
                filter(sex == 'Male') %>%

mean(male_height < 75) # calculate percentage 
## [1] 0.9408867

Answer : It seems about 0.9 percentage approximately. The calculated percentage of males is about 0.94.

Q5. Here is an eCDF of the murder rates across states: Knowing that there are 51 states (counting DC) and based on this plot, how many states have murder rates larger than 10 per 100,000 people?

murders %>% 
  mutate(murder_rate = total/population * 100000) %>%
  filter(murder_rate > 10) %>% 
  length()
## [1] 6

Answer : It seems that the raise of percentage is approximately about 0.1 (It will be 5 states 51 * 0.1 = 5) when murder rates larger than 10 per 100,000 people. The calculated count of states is 6.

Q6. Based on the eCDF above, which of the following statements are true:

Answer :
(a) About half the states have murder rates above 7 per 100,000 and the other half below. -> It seems about 3 ~ 4 has the percentage of 0.5
(b) Most states have murder rates below 2 per 100,000. -> The steepest percentage change occurs in 4 ~ 7. So most states have murder rates about 4 ~ 7.
(c) All the states have murder rate above 2 per 100,000. -> The states have murders rate has percentage about 0.4.
(d) With the exception of 4 states, the murder rates are below 5 per 100,000.(True, same result in Q5.)

heights %>%

Q8. About what percentage are shorter than 60 inches?

heights %>% 
  mutate(target = case_when(
    height < 60 ~ 'Target',
    height >= 60 ~ 'Non Target'         # Make category to make frequency table.
  )) %>%
  group_by(target) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(MEAN = round(n/sum(n),3)) %>% 
  select(target, MEAN)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   target      MEAN
##   <chr>      <dbl>
## 1 Non Target 0.981
## 2 Target     0.019

Answer : Percentage of height is about 1.9%, So the answer is (a).

Q9. Based on the density plot below, about what proportion of US states have populations larger than 10 million?

murders %>% 
  mutate(target = case_when(
    population >= 10000000 ~ 'Target',
    population < 10000000 ~ 'Non Target'         # Make category to make frequency table.
  )) %>%
  group_by(target) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(MEAN = round(n/sum(n),3)) %>% 
  select(target, MEAN)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   target      MEAN
##   <chr>      <dbl>
## 1 Non Target 0.863
## 2 Target     0.137

Answer : It seems about 7 ~ 10 approximately ( (0.6 + 0.1) * 20 / 2 = 7).The calculated proportion of US states have populations larger than 10 millon is about 0.137.

08 Visualizing data distributions : Exercise 66 page - 73 page

Q1. Now we are going to use the geom_histogram function to make a histogram of the heights in the height data frame. Make a histogram of all the plots. What is the variable containing the heights?

Answer : variable ‘height’ contians heights.

Q2.Now create a ggplot object using the pipe to assign the heights data to a ggplot object. Assign height to the x values through the aes function.

heights %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height))

Q3. Now we are ready to add a layer to actually make the histogram. Use the object created in the previous exercise and the geom_histogram function to make the histogram.

heights %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height)) + 
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Q4. Note that when we run the code in the previous exercise we get the warning: stat_bin() using bins = 30. Pick better value with binwidth. Use the binwidth argument to change the histogram made in the previous exercise to use bins of size 1 inch.

heights %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)

Q5. Instead of a histogram, we are going to make a smooth density plot. In this case we will not make an object, but instead render the plot with one line of code. Change the geometry in the code previously used to make a smooth density instead of a histogram.

heights %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5)

Q6. Now we are going to make a density plot for males and females separately. We can do this using the group argument. We assign groups via the aesthetic mapping as each point needs to a group before making the calculations needed to estimate a density.

heights %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height, group = sex)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5)

Q7. We can also assign groups through the color argument. This has the added benefit that it uses color to distinguish the groups. Change the code above to use color.

heights %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height, group = sex, color = sex)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5)

Q8. We can also assign groups through the fill argument. This has the added benefit that it uses colors to distinguish the groups, like this:

heights %>%
ggplot(aes(height, fill = sex)) + geom_density()

However, here the second density is drawn over the other. We can make the curves more visible by using alpha blending to add transparency. Set the alpha parameter to 0.2 in the geom_density function to make this change.

heights %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height, fill = sex)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.2)
